WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.700 --> 00:00:03.970
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington DC.

00:00:23.070 --> 00:00:24.520
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: Good
evening everybody.

00:00:24.520 --> 00:00:27.440
It's a great pleasure to
see you all here tonight.

00:00:27.440 --> 00:00:28.740
My name is David Plylar.

00:00:28.740 --> 00:00:30.710
I'm in the music division.

00:00:30.710 --> 00:00:32.570
I'm a music specialist there.

00:00:32.570 --> 00:00:35.520
And we have a real treat for you

00:00:35.520 --> 00:00:38.440
for our preconcert
conversation this evening.

00:00:38.440 --> 00:00:40.930
We have composer and
pianist Frederic Rzewski,

00:00:40.930 --> 00:00:46.540
who will be performing tonight as
-- his own music, which will be --

00:00:46.540 --> 00:00:50.320
we'll have a chance to hear
two piano pieces as well

00:00:50.320 --> 00:00:53.240
as the world premiere of a new
piece for violin and piano.

00:00:53.240 --> 00:00:55.000
So, we'll talk a bit about that.

00:00:55.000 --> 00:00:58.420
And I also have Charlton
Lee, who's the violist

00:00:58.420 --> 00:01:00.890
with the Del Sol String
Quartet, and they've been

00:01:00.890 --> 00:01:04.770
with us all week doing
really excellent work,

00:01:04.770 --> 00:01:10.430
using our instruments, and last
night they performed the String

00:01:10.430 --> 00:01:15.400
Quartet from 1955, and we'll
speak a bit about that as well.

00:01:15.400 --> 00:01:18.510
So, if you could just join
me in welcoming our guests.

00:01:18.510 --> 00:01:25.110
[ Applause ]

00:01:25.110 --> 00:01:27.990
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: I'd like to start
with something that's a bit unusual

00:01:27.990 --> 00:01:30.800
for me, which is not a
question, but rather a statement,

00:01:30.800 --> 00:01:35.460
and this is that I had
the opportunity in 2012

00:01:35.460 --> 00:01:38.970
to put together a chamber
concert in South Africa

00:01:38.970 --> 00:01:43.430
at the Grahamstown Festival,
which is kind of an obscure part

00:01:43.430 --> 00:01:50.260 position:56%
of South Africa, and we programmed
Coming Together at that performance.

00:01:50.260 --> 00:01:52.970
And what was an interesting
thing that happened was

00:01:52.970 --> 00:02:00.640 position:56%
that when we gave the performance we
had this huge up swell of gratitude

00:02:00.640 --> 00:02:04.460
and thanks from the audience
for that particular piece

00:02:04.460 --> 00:02:08.650 position:56%
and people had come in from all over
the place just to hear that piece.

00:02:08.650 --> 00:02:10.160
I thought it was the Dallapiccola

00:02:10.160 --> 00:02:13.460
that we had also programmed,
but it wasn't that.

00:02:13.460 --> 00:02:15.180
[laughter] Although that
was also a nice piece.

00:02:15.180 --> 00:02:20.740
But there -- it spoke to me at
a time that there's this element

00:02:20.740 --> 00:02:24.950 position:56%
to your music and it's -- of course
you write lots of different music --

00:02:24.950 --> 00:02:29.150
that tends to reach many
different types of people.

00:02:29.150 --> 00:02:33.090
And I just thought that I'd
share that as a starting point,

00:02:33.090 --> 00:02:36.970
that I had a very positive
experience in that light.

00:02:40.300 --> 00:02:41.810
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski:
I'm glad to hear that.

00:02:41.810 --> 00:02:43.110
I didn't know that.

00:02:43.110 --> 00:02:46.830
Do you know why people
-- ?[laughter]

00:02:46.830 --> 00:02:49.780
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: This I do
not know, but they just said

00:02:49.780 --> 00:02:52.550
that they were fans of
your music and so just --

00:02:52.550 --> 00:02:55.720
it wasn't often performed there.

00:02:55.720 --> 00:02:57.020
So --

00:02:57.020 --> 00:02:58.320
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: Probably not.

00:02:58.320 --> 00:03:00.670
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: Yeah, so it
was a chance to hear it I think.

00:03:00.670 --> 00:03:03.570
Hearing music live is just
also one of those things

00:03:03.570 --> 00:03:06.670
that they greatly valued.

00:03:06.670 --> 00:03:07.970
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: Well,

00:03:07.970 --> 00:03:10.600
it's funny because I had a
similar experience in Athens.

00:03:10.600 --> 00:03:17.690
I went to Athens a little more than
a year ago and a lot of people came

00:03:17.690 --> 00:03:27.280 position:56%
to my concert and it turned out most
of them were anarchists [laughter]

00:03:29.570 --> 00:03:35.610
and that this piece had been
played a number of times in Athens,

00:03:35.610 --> 00:03:41.330
and of course the guy who wrote
the text was himself an anarchist.

00:03:41.330 --> 00:03:45.410
So, there was some
connection there and there --

00:03:45.410 --> 00:03:48.530
in Athens there are
lots of anarchists.

00:03:48.530 --> 00:03:50.660
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: [laughs] Sure.

00:03:50.660 --> 00:03:53.850
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: But
more than that I don't know.

00:03:53.850 --> 00:03:55.630
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: I'm not sure
they're a particular [inaudible],

00:03:55.630 --> 00:03:57.400 position:56%
but they certainly enjoyed the music

00:03:57.400 --> 00:03:58.720
and the performance
[laughs] to be sure.

00:03:58.720 --> 00:04:00.020
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: Well, good.

00:04:00.020 --> 00:04:01.320
Yeah.

00:04:01.320 --> 00:04:03.160
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: Well, I
thought we'd start with --

00:04:03.160 --> 00:04:06.570
I don't know how many people in
this audience were able to come

00:04:06.570 --> 00:04:09.910
to the concert last night,
but we had a very -- Oh, good.

00:04:09.910 --> 00:04:11.720
I'm glad to see that
some of you were able to.

00:04:11.720 --> 00:04:16.310
It was a very unique experience,
and not just for us, the audience,

00:04:16.310 --> 00:04:20.900
but also for you, I would
imagine, in that there was a piece

00:04:20.900 --> 00:04:23.700
that you had written
when you were 16 or 17.

00:04:23.700 --> 00:04:25.100
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: That's right.

00:04:25.100 --> 00:04:26.900
Both actually.

00:04:26.900 --> 00:04:28.200
[inaudible]

00:04:28.200 --> 00:04:29.500 position:56%
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: [laughs] Straddled.

00:04:29.500 --> 00:04:34.560
And I guess I'm just wondering what
that experience would be like to --

00:04:34.560 --> 00:04:36.410
you hadn't ever had
a chance to hear --

00:04:36.410 --> 00:04:40.270 position:56%
you had your experience with it
composing it, clearly invested a lot

00:04:40.270 --> 00:04:44.910
of energy, and invested
time, and thought into it.

00:04:44.910 --> 00:04:46.210
At least it seemed to --

00:04:46.210 --> 00:04:48.930
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: I was a
student and I didn't know anything

00:04:48.930 --> 00:04:51.110
about anything and I
still don't, right?

00:04:51.110 --> 00:04:57.380
Truly. [laughter] But I mean,
string quartet, I only knew --

00:04:57.380 --> 00:05:01.320
I listened to a lot of
records, but I never played a --

00:05:01.320 --> 00:05:07.650
I mean I tried to play the cello
once and I even tried the viola,

00:05:07.650 --> 00:05:10.770
but you know there's a
kind of fundamental gap

00:05:10.770 --> 00:05:16.150
between keyboard players
and, you know,

00:05:16.150 --> 00:05:21.720
it's two completely different
universes and of course the thing

00:05:21.720 --> 00:05:26.220
about a piano or a keyboard
instrument is that it's a machine,

00:05:26.220 --> 00:05:33.960
a labor saving device
for playing lute music.

00:05:33.960 --> 00:05:37.150
[laughter] Well, historically
that is in fact the case

00:05:37.150 --> 00:05:41.390
because the lute is a
notoriously difficult instrument,

00:05:41.390 --> 00:05:50.020
as I guess you know, and the
keyboard was developed as a way

00:05:50.020 --> 00:05:53.970
of making it more available.

00:05:53.970 --> 00:05:57.010
I mean and you can see that
in renaissance paintings.

00:05:57.010 --> 00:06:01.570
It's the lute -- only
angels play lutes.

00:06:03.060 --> 00:06:07.730
[laughter] So -- but everybody
can play a keyboard instrument.

00:06:07.730 --> 00:06:09.530
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: I can't.

00:06:09.530 --> 00:06:12.930
[laughter]

00:06:12.930 --> 00:06:14.610
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski:
Well, that's what it is.

00:06:14.610 --> 00:06:18.350
And I mean, you know, I
don't know how I got into it,

00:06:18.350 --> 00:06:21.770
but anyhow what I really
wanted to say is

00:06:21.770 --> 00:06:24.610
that your performance
was spectacular.

00:06:24.610 --> 00:06:25.910
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: Thank you.

00:06:25.910 --> 00:06:27.370
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski:
I mean, it really was.

00:06:27.370 --> 00:06:29.520
[ Applause ]

00:06:29.520 --> 00:06:31.970
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: I had
never heard your quartet before,

00:06:31.970 --> 00:06:34.600
but it's really fantastic.

00:06:34.600 --> 00:06:36.610
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: Thank
you very much.

00:06:36.610 --> 00:06:37.910
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski:
Aside from the fact

00:06:37.910 --> 00:06:42.150
that you obviously worked very
hard on this particular thing,

00:06:42.150 --> 00:06:46.540 position:56%
I can see that you're, you know, a
real quartet and those things aren't

00:06:46.540 --> 00:06:53.360 position:56%
so common these days, but -- So, I'm
going to definitely check you out.

00:06:55.280 --> 00:06:56.580
[laughter] But thanks anyway.

00:06:56.580 --> 00:06:59.920
I mean it was fantastic because
my piece is, you know, basically,

00:06:59.920 --> 00:07:02.990
you know, just a student exercise.

00:07:02.990 --> 00:07:05.750
It's not so bad, but it isn't
really that [laughter] exciting.

00:07:05.750 --> 00:07:07.050
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: [laughing]
Not at all.

00:07:07.050 --> 00:07:09.050 position:56%
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: What I wouldn't say
is your standard student exercise.

00:07:09.050 --> 00:07:12.550
I don't remember too many
16-17 year olds who really --

00:07:12.550 --> 00:07:13.850
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: Well I --

00:07:13.850 --> 00:07:15.150
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: Mendelssohn
comes to mind.

00:07:15.150 --> 00:07:16.920
[laughter]

00:07:16.920 --> 00:07:20.030
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: Well, I was
trying to be avant-garde also

00:07:20.030 --> 00:07:25.670
and so forth and, you know, I was
trying to do all kinds of things,

00:07:25.670 --> 00:07:28.610
but without really know howing
-- [laughs] how to do them.

00:07:28.610 --> 00:07:33.410
And it's just as well it
waited 60 years to be performed

00:07:33.410 --> 00:07:38.200
because if it had been informed
then -- been performed then --

00:07:38.200 --> 00:07:40.400
then probably some
professor would have said,

00:07:40.400 --> 00:07:42.520
"Look dear take this
stuff out [laughter]

00:07:42.520 --> 00:07:45.360
because you can't have
these glissandi,

00:07:45.360 --> 00:07:47.150
you know, that's ridiculous."

00:07:47.150 --> 00:07:50.880
And in fact [laughs]
they are ridiculous.

00:07:52.180 --> 00:07:56.260
[laughter] But the extraordinary
thing about your performance was

00:07:56.260 --> 00:07:59.620 position:56%
that you did exactly what's written.

00:07:59.620 --> 00:08:03.590
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: Well, we thought
about it and we said, "Well,

00:08:03.590 --> 00:08:05.840
he was 17 and he probably said,

00:08:05.840 --> 00:08:10.330
'I don't care!'" [laughter]
So, we did it.

00:08:10.330 --> 00:08:11.630
[laughter]

00:08:11.630 --> 00:08:12.930
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: Yes, you
know, I mean I didn't expect that.

00:08:12.930 --> 00:08:20.070
I expected that you were
going to like, you know,

00:08:20.070 --> 00:08:22.710 position:56%
smooth out the [laughs] funny parts.

00:08:22.710 --> 00:08:24.560
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: I think
because we work so much

00:08:24.560 --> 00:08:27.900
with living composers we're
used to starting from the point

00:08:27.900 --> 00:08:31.160 position:56%
of doing exactly what's on the page
and then if they think it doesn't --

00:08:31.160 --> 00:08:34.030
if they don't like it they can
change it and then we'll change it.

00:08:34.030 --> 00:08:36.900 position:56%
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: Well, that brings
up an interesting question Charlton,

00:08:36.900 --> 00:08:40.960
with the process of preparing
this particular piece you know

00:08:40.960 --> 00:08:43.040
that you're going to have
the opportunity to speak

00:08:43.040 --> 00:08:46.320
with the composer, but it's at
such a remove that it's really

00:08:46.320 --> 00:08:49.460
like everybody's coming to this
piece as if it were a new piece.

00:08:49.460 --> 00:08:52.250
Did that affect the way -- or
did you still just go at it just

00:08:52.250 --> 00:08:55.630
as if it were a new piece
that's put in front of you?

00:08:55.630 --> 00:08:58.210
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: We still --
we treat every piece that way.

00:08:58.210 --> 00:09:03.550
So, even the two pieces on
these programs by the composers

00:09:03.550 --> 00:09:06.350
who are deceased, Crawford
[assumed spelling] and Ontile,

00:09:06.350 --> 00:09:09.100 position:56%
[phonetic spelling] we still
approached them as if they're living

00:09:09.100 --> 00:09:12.550
and then -- with like for example
the other day when you brought

00:09:12.550 --> 00:09:16.270
out those manuscripts, that was a
treat, and then we can look and,

00:09:16.270 --> 00:09:17.570
you know, they have notes written.

00:09:17.570 --> 00:09:20.990
It's like, mistake
here, tempo change here,

00:09:20.990 --> 00:09:22.880
it's like all this
great information.

00:09:22.880 --> 00:09:24.750
Then we of course copy them over.

00:09:24.750 --> 00:09:26.050
[laughter]

00:09:26.050 --> 00:09:28.230 position:56%
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: And actually I
think you did some adaptations based

00:09:28.230 --> 00:09:30.120
on little minor notes.

00:09:30.120 --> 00:09:31.420
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: Yeah, we did.

00:09:31.420 --> 00:09:32.740
Yeah, there was some
-- in the Ontile --

00:09:32.740 --> 00:09:36.430
let's see, when we recorded
the Ontile we had --

00:09:36.430 --> 00:09:41.190
there was one notation where he
crossed out one section and --

00:09:41.190 --> 00:09:45.010
but this time around we felt like,
actually it makes sense with it.

00:09:45.010 --> 00:09:47.210
Well, you can tell us tonight
if it works or not, but --

00:09:47.210 --> 00:09:49.840
[laughter] So, we kept
the whole thing this time.

00:09:49.840 --> 00:09:53.850 position:56%
Yeah, it's all the way -- it's all
what he wrote the first time around.

00:09:53.850 --> 00:09:55.450
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: The
Crawford is extraordinary.

00:09:55.450 --> 00:09:56.940
I didn't know this piece.

00:09:56.940 --> 00:09:58.240
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: It's incredible.

00:09:58.240 --> 00:09:59.810
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski:
Especially the second movement.

00:09:59.810 --> 00:10:01.110
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: Yeah.

00:10:01.110 --> 00:10:02.410
[laughs] That's --

00:10:02.410 --> 00:10:03.710
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski:
No, that really is --

00:10:03.710 --> 00:10:05.400
I mean that was an eye --
an ear -- opener for me.

00:10:05.400 --> 00:10:06.820
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: Yeah.

00:10:06.820 --> 00:10:10.630
No, she -- we were talking
as we were working in depth

00:10:10.630 --> 00:10:16.220
on this piece we were saying that
because she knew this young fellow

00:10:16.220 --> 00:10:23.520
at the time named -- uh oh,
now I'm blanking on a very --

00:10:23.520 --> 00:10:25.750
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski:
You mean knew him in --

00:10:25.750 --> 00:10:28.240
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: Mister
Elliot Carter.

00:10:28.240 --> 00:10:33.540 position:56%
So, he was her kind of a -- you know
he was a younger composer who's kind

00:10:33.540 --> 00:10:35.910
of hanging out with
them a little bit.

00:10:35.910 --> 00:10:37.210
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: Them who?

00:10:37.210 --> 00:10:38.810
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: The
Seegers and other people.

00:10:38.810 --> 00:10:40.110
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: both of them?

00:10:40.110 --> 00:10:41.410
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: I think so, yes.

00:10:41.410 --> 00:10:42.830
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: This
was before she was married.

00:10:42.830 --> 00:10:44.220
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: I'm
not sure exactly when --

00:10:44.220 --> 00:10:45.520
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: It
says so in the program.

00:10:45.520 --> 00:10:48.180 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: Okay, there you go.

00:10:48.180 --> 00:10:49.720
And -- oh no, this piece for sure.

00:10:49.720 --> 00:10:51.020
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: This piece.

00:10:51.020 --> 00:10:52.850
This was written a year
before she was married.

00:10:52.850 --> 00:10:54.150
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: That's right.

00:10:54.150 --> 00:10:55.450
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: Which is a --

00:10:55.450 --> 00:10:57.350
you know normally it's
not so significant,

00:10:57.350 --> 00:11:00.840
but I mean the only thing I
really know about this woman is

00:11:00.840 --> 00:11:03.030
that she basically
stopped composing.

00:11:03.030 --> 00:11:04.330
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: It's a pity.

00:11:04.330 --> 00:11:05.630
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: Well,

00:11:05.630 --> 00:11:10.550
I'm not sure what that's all
about, but it's not unusual.

00:11:10.550 --> 00:11:13.300
Of course the same thing
was true of Moller's wife.

00:11:13.300 --> 00:11:14.600
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: Right.

00:11:14.600 --> 00:11:15.900
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: Same thing.

00:11:15.900 --> 00:11:17.200
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: That's right.

00:11:17.200 --> 00:11:18.820
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: And,
you know I mean it's a --

00:11:18.820 --> 00:11:24.210
I presume probably very
common in, you know --

00:11:24.210 --> 00:11:25.510
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: Right.

00:11:25.510 --> 00:11:26.810
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: It's
definitely a complicated issue

00:11:26.810 --> 00:11:29.240
that has been written
about quite a bit recently.

00:11:29.240 --> 00:11:32.960
Judith Tick definitely approaches
it in her biography and some essays

00:11:32.960 --> 00:11:36.610
about it, but yes,
but Carter wasn't --

00:11:36.610 --> 00:11:40.180 position:56%
I believe those first string quartet
was actually influenced by --

00:11:40.180 --> 00:11:41.480
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: I think a lot

00:11:41.480 --> 00:11:43.450
of his ideas [laughs] were
influenced by this piece.

00:11:43.450 --> 00:11:44.750
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: By this piece.

00:11:44.750 --> 00:11:46.170
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: Yeah, exactly.

00:11:46.170 --> 00:11:50.020
A lot of the polyrhythms
and the voicing --

00:11:50.020 --> 00:11:52.000
voices crossing and all this stuff.

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:54.440
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: But he didn't
start doing that kind of thing --

00:11:54.440 --> 00:11:56.080
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: Until
about 15 years later.

00:11:56.080 --> 00:11:57.380
[laughs]

00:11:57.380 --> 00:11:58.680
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski:
Yeah, well more than that.

00:11:58.680 --> 00:11:59.980
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: Yeah, or more.

00:11:59.980 --> 00:12:01.280
Right.

00:12:01.280 --> 00:12:02.850 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: Because up
until 1950 or so he was writing sort

00:12:02.850 --> 00:12:08.700
of your standard neoclassic
Americana kind of thing.

00:12:09.830 --> 00:12:11.130
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: Yeah.

00:12:11.130 --> 00:12:12.430
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: Well,
was this when you --

00:12:12.430 --> 00:12:14.040
going back to when you
wrote the string quartet,

00:12:14.040 --> 00:12:17.310
was that the first writing
for strings that you had done,

00:12:17.310 --> 00:12:19.170
or had you done some
practice pieces before

00:12:19.170 --> 00:12:21.850
that for other versions
of the ensemble?

00:12:26.380 --> 00:12:27.680
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: Wait.

