00:26:18.390 --> 00:26:21.480
and secondly because if you do it

00:26:21.480 --> 00:26:24.030
for money it's not
going to be any good.

00:26:24.030 --> 00:26:25.760
That's all.

00:26:25.760 --> 00:26:28.670
And I guess there are
many examples of that.

00:26:28.670 --> 00:26:35.750
I mean priests for example,
or for that matter doctors.

00:26:35.750 --> 00:26:40.170
I met in Stanford -- I was in
Stanford University a few years ago

00:26:40.170 --> 00:26:42.960
and there was a Chinese
student -- pianist --

00:26:42.960 --> 00:26:46.200
you know, there are no
music majors in Stanford.

00:26:46.200 --> 00:26:50.690
You can major in different
things, but not music.

00:26:50.690 --> 00:26:55.790
So -- but many students
study music nonetheless.

00:26:55.790 --> 00:27:00.110
So, there was -- I was doing a
piano master class or something

00:27:00.110 --> 00:27:05.270
and there was somebody -- a Chinese
woman -- who played quite well.

00:27:05.270 --> 00:27:09.150
And so I talked to her afterwards
because I was interested,

00:27:09.150 --> 00:27:14.920
you know -- this was in
the nineties so it wasn't

00:27:14.920 --> 00:27:17.900
so -- it was a while ago.

00:27:17.900 --> 00:27:20.830
Before it was clear
whether China was --

00:27:20.830 --> 00:27:22.780
you know, which way China was going

00:27:22.780 --> 00:27:27.560
and it was still very much a
communist country, if you like.

00:27:27.560 --> 00:27:31.430
And so I asked her, "Well,
what are you really studying?"

00:27:31.430 --> 00:27:34.380
She said, "I'm studying medicine."

00:27:34.380 --> 00:27:37.040
So, I thought, "Well,
this is interesting."

00:27:37.040 --> 00:27:40.570
And, you know -- so I
asked her, "Are you --

00:27:40.570 --> 00:27:46.140
you want to become a doctor
because you want to help people

00:27:46.140 --> 00:27:49.470
or because you want to get rich?"

00:27:49.470 --> 00:27:56.660
And she went, [growls] "Get rich!"

00:27:56.660 --> 00:27:58.450
[laughter] So, you know, okay.

00:27:58.450 --> 00:28:03.270
This is certainly --
that's possible.

00:28:03.270 --> 00:28:07.500
But it's not really a good idea.

00:28:07.500 --> 00:28:11.270
I mean there are certain --

00:28:11.270 --> 00:28:16.840
there's a fundamental contradiction
there somewhere, it seems to me.

00:28:16.840 --> 00:28:22.300
And it certainly is true
in the case of composition.

00:28:22.300 --> 00:28:24.940
You just don't do it for money.

00:28:24.940 --> 00:28:27.680
So, you make a living
one way or another.

00:28:27.680 --> 00:28:31.990
Most people in this
country do it by teaching.

00:28:31.990 --> 00:28:34.840
Well, I would have done that
too, gladly, if I had been able

00:28:34.840 --> 00:28:37.040
to get a job, but I wasn't.

00:28:37.040 --> 00:28:42.040
So, I went to Europe and
did it some other way.

00:28:42.040 --> 00:28:45.850
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: Well, you also
had going for you the ability

00:28:45.850 --> 00:28:47.700
to perform your own
music, which was,

00:28:47.700 --> 00:28:51.830
I think, a helpful exponent of --

00:28:51.830 --> 00:28:53.130
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: Well, yes.

00:28:53.130 --> 00:28:59.690
It's good if you can -- if you're
a performing musician it's good

00:28:59.690 --> 00:29:03.790
to bring these two things
together as much as possible.

00:29:03.790 --> 00:29:06.690
I mean it's good to
get paid when you play,

00:29:06.690 --> 00:29:09.960
and that's actually becoming
more and more difficult

00:29:09.960 --> 00:29:11.810
as you -- I'm sure you will agree.

00:29:11.810 --> 00:29:13.110
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: Yes.

00:29:13.110 --> 00:29:18.080
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: There's less
and less money around for culture.

00:29:18.080 --> 00:29:19.480
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: That's right.

00:29:19.480 --> 00:29:20.780
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski:
But that's a long story.

00:29:20.780 --> 00:29:22.300
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: That's
a very big story.

00:29:22.300 --> 00:29:23.600
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: We
could talk about that

00:29:23.600 --> 00:29:24.900
for the rest of the night.

00:29:24.900 --> 00:29:26.200
[laughs]

00:29:26.200 --> 00:29:27.500
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: All night.

00:29:27.500 --> 00:29:28.800
[laughs]

00:29:28.800 --> 00:29:30.100
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: Well, one
other thing that we're going

00:29:30.100 --> 00:29:31.700
to be hearing tonight that I would
love to hear you say a few words

00:29:31.700 --> 00:29:35.000
about if you like,
would be the new piece,

00:29:35.000 --> 00:29:38.430
the new commission work
for violin and piano.

00:29:38.430 --> 00:29:41.470
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: Well, I did
write about it in the program notes

00:29:41.470 --> 00:29:45.780
and there's not really
much more to say about it.

00:29:45.780 --> 00:29:50.150 position:56%
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: Well, how much have
you composed for that medium before?

00:29:50.150 --> 00:29:51.450
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski:
For violin and piano?

00:29:51.450 --> 00:29:52.750
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: Yeah.

00:29:52.750 --> 00:29:54.050
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski:
Well, around the time

00:29:54.050 --> 00:29:58.270
of this piece you played last night
I also wrote a sonata for violin

00:29:58.270 --> 00:30:00.980
and piano and I think
maybe it got lost.

00:30:00.980 --> 00:30:02.280
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: Oh.

00:30:02.280 --> 00:30:04.280
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: At least
I don't know where it is.

00:30:04.280 --> 00:30:06.850
It's kind of in -- I remember
it's kind of in the style

00:30:06.850 --> 00:30:08.700
of Bartok or something like that.

00:30:08.700 --> 00:30:14.290
So -- and I tried writing for
violin and piano in the meantime,

00:30:14.290 --> 00:30:18.740
occasionally a few fiddle players
expressed some interest in it,

00:30:18.740 --> 00:30:21.190
but I didn't get very far.

00:30:21.190 --> 00:30:25.770
And as I say, I think it was
mainly because, you know,

00:30:25.770 --> 00:30:28.980
string players are
basically just not interested.

00:30:28.980 --> 00:30:36.090
And, in fact, it is kind of an
antiquated, or archaic, form.

00:30:36.090 --> 00:30:40.510
I mean, not string quartet
maybe, but say violin and piano,

00:30:40.510 --> 00:30:43.600
or if you think about it
there isn't really that much.

00:30:43.600 --> 00:30:47.350 position:56%
And for that matter, you know,
beside from the Shostakovich Sonata,

00:30:47.350 --> 00:30:50.580
what is there for viola
and piano for example.

00:30:50.580 --> 00:30:51.890
[laughter] I mean really?

00:30:51.890 --> 00:30:53.190
Do you ever -- ?

00:30:53.190 --> 00:30:54.490
You must know.

00:30:54.490 --> 00:30:56.420
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: Actually
I'm focusing so much

00:30:56.420 --> 00:30:58.460
on string quartets [laughs] I'm
not really paying attention.

00:30:58.460 --> 00:31:01.740
But there's actually
a lot being written.

00:31:01.740 --> 00:31:03.740
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: There
may be a lot written [laughs]

00:31:03.740 --> 00:31:07.100
but it doesn't get played and
that's probably a good thing.

00:31:07.100 --> 00:31:12.700
[laughter] Is there
any significant -- ?

00:31:12.700 --> 00:31:17.460 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: I'm so biased just
towards the string quartet it really

00:31:17.460 --> 00:31:18.760
isn't fair.

00:31:18.760 --> 00:31:20.060
[laughs]

00:31:20.060 --> 00:31:21.360
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: That's fine,
but what I'm saying is that yeah,

00:31:21.360 --> 00:31:25.370
I don't think it's -- you know
there may be string quartets,

00:31:25.370 --> 00:31:28.250
although there aren't
that many of those either.

00:31:28.250 --> 00:31:29.770
That, you know --

00:31:29.770 --> 00:31:31.070
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: There's a lot.

00:31:31.070 --> 00:31:35.040
Actually you should see the
piles of submissions we have.

00:31:35.040 --> 00:31:39.590
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: That may
well be that there is a lot.

00:31:39.590 --> 00:31:40.890
Somebody said something.

00:31:40.890 --> 00:31:42.190
--

00:31:42.190 --> 00:31:43.770
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: They
were just laughing.

00:31:43.770 --> 00:31:45.070
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski:
Oh, just laughing.

00:31:45.070 --> 00:31:46.370
Okay.

00:31:46.370 --> 00:31:48.380
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: Well, I think
that in any case there's --

00:31:48.380 --> 00:31:52.010
whether a medium is played out or
not there's always something to say

00:31:52.010 --> 00:31:54.060
in it I think and it seems like --

00:31:54.060 --> 00:31:56.940
what's an interesting thing is
that you've done this for us,

00:31:56.940 --> 00:31:58.550
and we'll get to hear this tonight.

00:31:58.550 --> 00:32:02.850
And kind of as a counterpart we
have the collaborative effort

00:32:02.850 --> 00:32:05.800
with the Philips Collection and
you'll be playing another violin

00:32:05.800 --> 00:32:08.430
and piano piece tomorrow there.

00:32:08.430 --> 00:32:10.410
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: Well,
this is a great idea.

00:32:10.410 --> 00:32:13.040
I mean, it's my own
point of view, but --

00:32:13.040 --> 00:32:14.340
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: Yeah,
we think so too.

00:32:14.340 --> 00:32:15.640
[laughs]

00:32:15.640 --> 00:32:16.940
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: But I think --
you know I think composers would --

00:32:16.940 --> 00:32:19.890
most composers would agree
because there isn't a whole lot

00:32:19.890 --> 00:32:24.910
of demand for violin and piano.

00:32:24.910 --> 00:32:28.600
It just seems like
it's an archaic forum

00:32:28.600 --> 00:32:34.740 position:56%
and therefore there isn't that much.

00:32:34.740 --> 00:32:36.240
So, I mean I don't know.

00:32:36.240 --> 00:32:37.570
We'll see what it's like.

00:32:37.570 --> 00:32:40.730
I have a pretty good idea of
what it's going to sound like

00:32:40.730 --> 00:32:43.310
and I think it's not so bad.

00:32:43.310 --> 00:32:48.570
But of course I'm the last
person [laughs] to judge.

00:32:48.570 --> 00:32:49.870
We'll see.

00:32:49.870 --> 00:32:57.940
But I -- but it's a good idea,
you know, to get people to do --

00:32:57.940 --> 00:33:03.930
get them back into this form
again because it seems to be --

00:33:03.930 --> 00:33:05.850
I don't know I can't get --

00:33:05.850 --> 00:33:08.850
I mean you probably know
more than I do about this.

00:33:08.850 --> 00:33:10.150
I mean --

00:33:10.150 --> 00:33:11.520
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: Well,
the library has a --

00:33:11.520 --> 00:33:15.390
this is funded through the McKim
Fund in the Library of Congress,

00:33:15.390 --> 00:33:18.680
which as many of you concert
goers who have been to lots

00:33:18.680 --> 00:33:22.450
of our concerts, it's a fund
that we've had in place for many,

00:33:22.450 --> 00:33:26.800
many years, I think since the
late sixties or early seventies,

00:33:26.800 --> 00:33:29.880
and it's commissioned -- I'm trying
to think of the number offhand --

00:33:29.880 --> 00:33:34.380
but a number of very large
-- of pieces of, you know,

00:33:34.380 --> 00:33:36.880
different styles, different
composers, all those types

00:33:36.880 --> 00:33:40.420 position:56%
of things, but including things
like the Carter duo and other things

00:33:40.420 --> 00:33:44.220
like that and some works
by Babbitt and it's a --

00:33:44.220 --> 00:33:48.460
it has a wide variety
of opportunities given

00:33:48.460 --> 00:33:49.870
for that particular ensemble,

00:33:49.870 --> 00:33:52.630
but funding requires it
to be violin and piano.

00:33:52.630 --> 00:33:56.930
So, that's one reason why we
stick with that when we do that.

00:33:56.930 --> 00:34:00.560
But it certainly has, I
think, enlarged the body

00:34:00.560 --> 00:34:02.980
of music available for that.

00:34:02.980 --> 00:34:06.130 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: I think I asked
you, when this first arose, I said,

00:34:06.130 --> 00:34:08.550
"Well, does it really
have to be violin?

00:34:08.550 --> 00:34:12.570 position:56%
For instance, couldn't it be viola?"

00:34:12.570 --> 00:34:14.450
[laughter] Well, my
daughter plays viola

00:34:14.450 --> 00:34:17.850
and of course I was
thinking about that.

00:34:17.850 --> 00:34:21.550
And David said, "Nope it
has to be violin and piano."

00:34:21.550 --> 00:34:22.850
[laughter]

00:34:22.850 --> 00:34:24.150
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: So,
we just need a new fund

00:34:24.150 --> 00:34:26.950
that covers viola and piano.

00:34:26.950 --> 00:34:29.100
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: Well, my
daughter has this particular point

00:34:29.100 --> 00:34:33.140
of view, she thinks that the
real instrument is the viola,

00:34:33.140 --> 00:34:36.830
after all violino is just
a little viola, that's all.

00:34:36.830 --> 00:34:41.680
[laughter] and the real instrument
is the viola and she thinks what --

00:34:41.680 --> 00:34:47.480 position:56%
you should just have a five stringed
viola, a viola with an E string

00:34:47.480 --> 00:34:50.760
and then get rid of the violin.

00:34:50.760 --> 00:34:52.060
[laughter]

00:34:52.060 --> 00:34:53.360
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: How do you
feel about that Charles?

00:34:53.360 --> 00:34:54.660
[laughter]

00:34:54.660 --> 00:34:56.120
&gt;&gt; That's how electronic
violins are made these days.

00:34:56.120 --> 00:34:57.420
[laughter]

00:34:57.420 --> 00:34:58.720
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski:
Yes, I know they --

00:34:58.720 --> 00:35:00.160
&gt;&gt; Electronic ones are made with
five -- exactly that, five strings.

00:35:00.160 --> 00:35:01.460 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: I know it does.

00:35:01.460 --> 00:35:02.760
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: I've even
seen some six stringed ones.

00:35:02.760 --> 00:35:04.260
[laughter]

00:35:04.260 --> 00:35:07.190
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: Well,
her point was that, you know,

00:35:07.190 --> 00:35:08.600
the thing about the violin --

00:35:08.600 --> 00:35:10.340
I think the dramatic part

00:35:10.340 --> 00:35:15.550
of the violin is the G
string, the low string.

00:35:15.550 --> 00:35:20.790
And she says the G string is
really much better on the viola.

00:35:20.790 --> 00:35:23.780
And, you know, actually it's
hard to argue with that.

00:35:23.780 --> 00:35:25.080
It's just --

00:35:25.080 --> 00:35:26.380
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: Then
you have the C string.

00:35:26.380 --> 00:35:27.680
[laughter]

00:35:27.680 --> 00:35:28.980
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski:
And then you have on top

00:35:28.980 --> 00:35:31.450
of that you have that
fantastic C string.

00:35:31.450 --> 00:35:36.150 position:56%
By the way, I did notice your --
you have a particular way of playing

00:35:36.150 --> 00:35:39.740
that -- you know the
viola doesn't often stick

00:35:39.740 --> 00:35:45.540 position:56%
out in a string quartet, and you do.

00:35:45.540 --> 00:35:47.320
[laughter] Was it because
of the instrument or --

00:35:47.320 --> 00:35:48.750
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: Are any
of my colleagues here?

00:35:48.750 --> 00:35:50.880
[laughter]

00:35:50.880 --> 00:35:53.210
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: No, my
question is -- I mean it --

00:35:53.210 --> 00:35:57.950
was the instrument unusually
strong or is it just your -- ?

00:35:57.950 --> 00:36:00.480
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: No, they
have the big instruments.

00:36:00.480 --> 00:36:03.890
The -- I mean, last night Ben
[assumed spelling] was playing the

00:36:03.890 --> 00:36:05.590 position:56%
Chrysler Coronary [assumed spelling]

00:36:05.590 --> 00:36:07.590
and Rick [assumed spelling]
was playing the Besk Strata

00:36:07.590 --> 00:36:08.890
[phonetic spelling].

00:36:08.890 --> 00:36:11.820
They should -- no,
it's probably just me.

00:36:11.820 --> 00:36:13.490
I like to play loud.

00:36:13.490 --> 00:36:14.850 position:56%
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: Just a power house.

00:36:14.850 --> 00:36:16.150
So, yeah.

00:36:16.150 --> 00:36:17.450
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: Yes.

00:36:17.450 --> 00:36:18.960
Well, yeah, I mean I
was impressed by that.

00:36:18.960 --> 00:36:23.290 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: I mean I -- there's
a wonderful quote from Michael Tree,

00:36:23.290 --> 00:36:25.060
[assumed spelling] the former
violist of the Guarneri Quartet,

00:36:25.060 --> 00:36:28.450
and he said that the violas
should always play louder

00:36:28.450 --> 00:36:31.460 position:56%
than his colleagues think he should.

00:36:31.460 --> 00:36:35.100
[laughter]

00:36:35.100 --> 00:36:37.680
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: Yeah, well
of course we're starting to get

00:36:37.680 --> 00:36:39.510
into the area of viola jokes.

00:36:39.510 --> 00:36:40.810
[laughter]

00:36:40.810 --> 00:36:46.310
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: Well, why don't
we take some more questions.

00:36:46.310 --> 00:36:49.070
There's a microphone
that will come to you.

00:36:49.070 --> 00:36:50.890
&gt;&gt; Hi, thanks.

00:36:50.890 --> 00:36:53.380
You said earlier that
-- or suggested that --

00:36:53.380 --> 00:36:55.120
much new music wasn't very good,

00:36:55.120 --> 00:36:57.450
but are there any contemporary
composers you particularly

00:36:57.450 --> 00:36:59.440
like or respect?

00:36:59.440 --> 00:37:02.130
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: Oh,
yeah quite a few of them.

00:37:02.130 --> 00:37:03.430
Yeah. Sure.

00:37:03.430 --> 00:37:08.640
I mean, actually there are a lot of
them and the interesting thing is

00:37:08.640 --> 00:37:12.630
that -- well it goes up and down,

00:37:12.630 --> 00:37:18.020
but there for a while there
it looked as though, you know,

00:37:18.020 --> 00:37:21.310 position:56%
composition might be on the way out.

00:37:21.310 --> 00:37:25.870
After all there's no reason why
it should stick around forever

00:37:25.870 --> 00:37:30.080
and we can see the art
of painting, for example,

00:37:30.080 --> 00:37:36.980
seems to be disappearing,
if not already gone.

00:37:36.980 --> 00:37:40.940
The art of painting with
oil colors, which has been

00:37:40.940 --> 00:37:44.550
around for say 600 years
or something like that,

00:37:44.550 --> 00:37:47.260
since Ja Do [phonetic
spelling], say.

00:37:47.260 --> 00:37:53.240
It's, you know, arguably finished

00:37:53.240 --> 00:37:58.370
because now we have
something called visual arts.

00:37:58.370 --> 00:38:00.780
Well, I've never seen a visual art.

00:38:00.780 --> 00:38:02.080
I don't know what it is.

00:38:02.080 --> 00:38:03.380
I know what painting is.

00:38:03.380 --> 00:38:06.870
I know what sculpture
is, but visual arts

00:38:06.870 --> 00:38:12.290
to me is a euphemism
synonymous with nothing.

00:38:12.290 --> 00:38:18.980
And the same thing may
be happening with music.

00:38:18.980 --> 00:38:24.790
It's clear to everybody I think
that the level of creative --

00:38:24.790 --> 00:38:28.980
the creative level of music
has been going down steadily

00:38:28.980 --> 00:38:34.330 position:56%
for the last 100 years, if not more.

00:38:34.330 --> 00:38:38.670
And I'm afraid since
Stockhausen was a good composer,

00:38:38.670 --> 00:38:42.850
but he wasn't as good
as Richard Strauss,

00:38:42.850 --> 00:38:47.800
who in turn was not
quite as good as Brahms.

00:38:47.800 --> 00:38:51.120
So, there is clearly
a steady decline

00:38:51.120 --> 00:38:55.250
in quality throughout the
twentieth century, which is --

00:38:55.250 --> 00:38:57.570
I mean you may argue with it.

00:38:57.570 --> 00:38:59.470
You may say, "Well,
actually, you know,

00:38:59.470 --> 00:39:02.140
Schoenberg was the greatest
composer who ever lived,

00:39:02.140 --> 00:39:05.660
but it won't convince most people.

00:39:05.660 --> 00:39:13.720
Of course he was a good composer,
but again so on and so forth --

00:39:13.720 --> 00:39:18.890
but whereas -- interestingly the
level of performance has gone

00:39:18.890 --> 00:39:20.950
in the opposite direction.

00:39:20.950 --> 00:39:27.760
The young performers of today
are better than Horowitz

00:39:27.760 --> 00:39:31.710
and you can hear that on -- one of
the advantages of the internet is

00:39:31.710 --> 00:39:37.570
that you can just push a button
and compare; [laughs] five seconds.

00:39:37.570 --> 00:39:42.970
And it's quite extraordinary
that this is true.

00:39:42.970 --> 00:39:45.170
So, it's not at all simple.

00:39:45.170 --> 00:39:50.020
It's a complex process and
of course that can be due

00:39:50.020 --> 00:39:51.660
to many different factors.

00:39:51.660 --> 00:39:56.780
One of them, for example, is the
radio and technology in general

00:39:56.780 --> 00:39:59.210 position:56%
and the media and the monopolization

00:39:59.210 --> 00:40:02.040
of the music industry
and etcetera, etcetera.

00:40:02.040 --> 00:40:06.830
I mean, basically capitalism
is not good for culture.

00:40:06.830 --> 00:40:12.710
Capitalism does not lead to
better art, on the contrary,

00:40:12.710 --> 00:40:18.990
it's destructive in many, many
ways including the [laughs] are

00:40:18.990 --> 00:40:24.690
of art and culture.

00:40:24.690 --> 00:40:28.560
It -- capitalism is --
it's time to get rid of it.

00:40:28.560 --> 00:40:30.380
[laughs] We need something else.

00:40:30.380 --> 00:40:33.180
I mean, this was not
always true of course.

00:40:33.180 --> 00:40:36.650
There -- even in the
nineteenth century much art

00:40:36.650 --> 00:40:47.680 position:56%
and culture owes its existence to
the fact that there were rich people

00:40:47.680 --> 00:40:49.910
around who could spend money on it.

00:40:49.910 --> 00:40:52.160
But today it is no longer true.

00:40:52.160 --> 00:40:56.450
It -- well, okay, this is again
a completely different thing.

00:40:56.450 --> 00:40:58.790
[laughs] The point is though
that yes, there are --

00:40:58.790 --> 00:41:00.980
yeah, and it's a complex
process and it --

00:41:00.980 --> 00:41:05.790
I think history goes in
both directions at once.

00:41:05.790 --> 00:41:09.720
It goes forward and it also
goes backward at the same time.

00:41:09.720 --> 00:41:16.700
So, for a while it looked as though
there were not very interesting

00:41:16.700 --> 00:41:21.290 position:56%
composers around, and of course
that varies from country to country.

00:41:21.290 --> 00:41:25.500
Unfortunately in this
country it's especially true.

00:41:25.500 --> 00:41:31.700
A lot of young composers
want to be pop stars.

00:41:32.750 --> 00:41:35.360
It's unfortunate, but it's true.

00:41:35.360 --> 00:41:39.020
And of course most of them
won't become pop stars,

00:41:39.020 --> 00:41:43.040
but some of them do, and some
of them even get commissions

00:41:43.040 --> 00:41:46.720
from the Metropolitan
Opera or wherever

00:41:46.720 --> 00:41:51.590
and of course you could say,
"Well, this has always been true."

00:41:51.590 --> 00:41:55.440
Maybe, but -- So, it's hard --

00:41:55.440 --> 00:42:02.490
I can't point to really
any really significant,

00:42:02.490 --> 00:42:04.920
interesting young composers
in this country.

00:42:04.920 --> 00:42:10.590
I can point to a few in
some European countries.

00:42:10.590 --> 00:42:13.950
Now of course I don't know
everything and I don't --

00:42:13.950 --> 00:42:17.850
and most of the time I don't live
here so I -- there probably --

00:42:17.850 --> 00:42:20.060
and maybe there are
some young people

00:42:20.060 --> 00:42:24.690
around who are very interesting
and who I just don't know.

00:42:24.690 --> 00:42:28.790
And I would hope that
would be the case.

00:42:28.790 --> 00:42:33.120
Probably if Ursula Oppens were
here she would probably be already

00:42:33.120 --> 00:42:36.560
protesting, loudly, and saying,
you know, there's this one,

00:42:36.560 --> 00:42:40.040
and this one, and this one, and
this one, and of course I know

00:42:40.040 --> 00:42:44.650
from long friendship that it's
better not to argue with Ursula.

00:42:46.060 --> 00:42:51.740
[laughter] And [laughs] I would be
very happy if that were the case,

00:42:51.740 --> 00:42:57.810
but there are some -- a few
interesting younger composers

00:42:57.810 --> 00:43:00.600
around in certain places.

00:43:00.600 --> 00:43:07.050
So, I wouldn't be surprised if
there's a new kind of generation

00:43:07.050 --> 00:43:14.090
that appears that -- One thing that
I think was not good was serialism.

00:43:14.090 --> 00:43:19.340
I think serialism did not help
to advance the art of music.

00:43:19.340 --> 00:43:26.760
It had a definitely a depressing
quality on the level of music.

00:43:26.760 --> 00:43:32.940
A lot of music was produced that
has this academic quality about it,

00:43:32.940 --> 00:43:37.690
which did not guarantee its
future; on the contrary.

00:43:37.690 --> 00:43:44.090
But even worse, I would say,
was what is known as minimalism.

00:43:44.090 --> 00:43:46.310
It's even worse.

00:43:46.310 --> 00:43:50.320
And -- but fortunately now you
have some younger composers

00:43:50.320 --> 00:43:54.910
who not only don't give a
damn about serial music,

00:43:54.910 --> 00:44:01.670
which is already being forgotten,
but even they don't give a damn

00:44:01.670 --> 00:44:06.740
about minimalism either
and this kind of green mold

00:44:06.740 --> 00:44:10.470
or fungus is growing
on this kind of music,

00:44:10.470 --> 00:44:14.200
which before the people
are even dead.

00:44:14.200 --> 00:44:17.720
[laughter] At least,
you know, Stockhausen

00:44:17.720 --> 00:44:20.510
and Boulez are now gone, but --

00:44:20.510 --> 00:44:25.390
[ Laughter ]

00:44:25.390 --> 00:44:29.160
But to see this happening already,
you know, this mold growing

00:44:29.160 --> 00:44:33.740
on people who are still there,
it's kind of frightening.

00:44:33.740 --> 00:44:38.480 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: Well, it's kind of
curious that tonight the other piece

00:44:38.480 --> 00:44:41.930
that we're playing tonight is
by Ben Johnston and so that --

00:44:41.930 --> 00:44:43.750
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: Well,
he was a very good composer.

00:44:43.750 --> 00:44:45.050
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: And still is.

00:44:45.050 --> 00:44:46.350
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: And still is!

00:44:46.350 --> 00:44:48.350
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: He's still alive.

00:44:48.350 --> 00:44:50.910
[laughter] He is 90, to be fair.

00:44:50.910 --> 00:44:54.520
But he would -- in many ways --
would probably be the antithesis

00:44:54.520 --> 00:44:59.880
of a serialist composer because his
whole paradigm was just intonation.

00:44:59.880 --> 00:45:03.160
So, he wanted pure ratios
between the pitches.

00:45:03.160 --> 00:45:07.840
And so everything was blending in
a beautiful wave, not strange wave.

00:45:07.840 --> 00:45:10.850
But so the whole idea about
serialism and, you know,

00:45:10.850 --> 00:45:12.960
each half step being a
square root of two --

00:45:12.960 --> 00:45:14.800
oh no, twelfth root of
two, or some crazy --

00:45:14.800 --> 00:45:19.360
you know, it's like was
completely against his ideas.

00:45:19.360 --> 00:45:23.490
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: Well, you
know, the reality is that these --

00:45:23.490 --> 00:45:26.730
what you're talking
about is just theory.

00:45:26.730 --> 00:45:28.030
That's mathematics.

00:45:28.030 --> 00:45:29.330
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: Yes.

00:45:29.330 --> 00:45:30.630
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: I mean,
you look at a real piano

00:45:30.630 --> 00:45:34.550
after the piano tuner is done with
it, it has absolutely nothing to do

00:45:34.550 --> 00:45:37.010
with the twelfth root
[laughing] of two.

00:45:37.010 --> 00:45:40.880
It's whatever the piano
tuner thinks sounded good.

00:45:40.880 --> 00:45:42.790
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: He has
to make magic with it.

00:45:42.790 --> 00:45:45.680 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: And in fact all
pianos are completely out of tune.

00:45:45.680 --> 00:45:46.980
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: Right.

00:45:46.980 --> 00:45:49.670
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: And if they
weren't they wouldn't sound good.

00:45:49.670 --> 00:45:51.090
[laughter]

00:45:51.090 --> 00:45:53.720
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: Actually I've
heard some that have been --

00:45:53.720 --> 00:45:57.990
but then you can only play
specific pieces on them.

00:45:57.990 --> 00:45:59.960
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: No.

00:45:59.960 --> 00:46:05.400
The piano I'm going to play on
tonight is a good instrument.

00:46:05.400 --> 00:46:10.200
I don't know if anybody
tuned it [laughter] recently.

00:46:10.200 --> 00:46:11.500
They probably did, right?

00:46:11.500 --> 00:46:13.820
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: They were
tuning just as I came in.

00:46:13.820 --> 00:46:15.340
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: Well,
I worked on it this morning.

00:46:15.340 --> 00:46:18.120
It sounded very good
even before it was tuned.

00:46:18.120 --> 00:46:21.040
[laughter] It's probably going
to sound even better now.

00:46:21.040 --> 00:46:23.980
But you know piano tuners have
this thing that they talk about,

00:46:23.980 --> 00:46:29.200
which I have never understood,
it's called harmonisity.

00:46:29.200 --> 00:46:30.580
You know what it is?

00:46:30.580 --> 00:46:35.730
It's something about how the spaces
between the intervals gets bigger

00:46:35.730 --> 00:46:41.250
as you go from the middle of the
instrument to the outer extremes.

00:46:41.250 --> 00:46:45.070
But I have never understood
[laughs] what that actually means.

00:46:45.070 --> 00:46:49.600
I think it just means that piano
tuners have found this particular

00:46:49.600 --> 00:46:54.030
way of making the instrument
sound good and it probably varies

00:46:54.030 --> 00:46:55.820
from instrument to instrument.

00:46:55.820 --> 00:46:58.990
So, this twelfth root of
two business is, you know,

00:46:58.990 --> 00:47:01.520
it's like E equals MC squared.

00:47:01.520 --> 00:47:04.650
You know, maybe it's
true [laughs] but --

00:47:04.650 --> 00:47:07.280
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: I think it's
-- for us as string players,

00:47:07.280 --> 00:47:09.950
of course we're particularly
sensitive to those,

00:47:09.950 --> 00:47:11.950
and so to us the piano
basically sounds

00:47:11.950 --> 00:47:13.410
out of tune, I'm sorry to say.

00:47:13.410 --> 00:47:14.710
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski:
Well, it is out of tune.

00:47:14.710 --> 00:47:16.920
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: Exactly,
but we hear it.

00:47:16.920 --> 00:47:21.510
[laughs] So -- and I think --
So, what we are able to do,

00:47:21.510 --> 00:47:24.440
and if you're tuning --
because our tendency is

00:47:24.440 --> 00:47:27.470
to tune more pure,
as much as we can.

00:47:27.470 --> 00:47:29.510
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: Pure?

00:47:29.510 --> 00:47:32.380
Oh, don't give me that.

00:47:32.380 --> 00:47:33.680
[laughter]

00:47:33.680 --> 00:47:34.980
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: Tuning more

00:47:34.980 --> 00:47:38.440
with smaller ratios,
let's put it that way.

00:47:38.440 --> 00:47:39.740
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: Ratios?

00:47:39.740 --> 00:47:41.040
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: Ratios.

00:47:41.040 --> 00:47:42.340
Like --

00:47:42.340 --> 00:47:43.640
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: So,
like smaller numbers?

00:47:43.640 --> 00:47:44.940
[inaudible]

00:47:44.940 --> 00:47:46.240
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: Right.

00:47:46.240 --> 00:47:47.940
So, a fifth being a
three to two match.

00:47:47.940 --> 00:47:49.620
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: Okay,
I'll take your word for it.

00:47:49.620 --> 00:47:51.680
I've never understood these things.

00:47:51.680 --> 00:47:56.700
So, I don't know, maybe.

00:47:56.700 --> 00:48:01.350
Okay, but any rate, Ben Johnston,
whether he believes this stuff

00:48:01.350 --> 00:48:02.970
or not, it doesn't really matter.

00:48:02.970 --> 00:48:06.220
The fact was that he wrote --
has written some good music.

00:48:06.220 --> 00:48:07.520
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: Exactly.

00:48:07.520 --> 00:48:08.820
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: Yeah.

00:48:08.820 --> 00:48:10.120
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: The
music is really fun.

00:48:10.120 --> 00:48:13.240
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: How
he did it, who cares.

00:48:13.240 --> 00:48:14.540
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: I
think we have time

00:48:14.540 --> 00:48:16.170
for just about one more question.

00:48:16.170 --> 00:48:20.550
&gt;&gt; Okay. Well, I hope,
no [inaudible].

00:48:20.550 --> 00:48:21.850
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: Let's say two.

00:48:21.850 --> 00:48:23.210
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: Okay,
two more questions.

00:48:23.210 --> 00:48:24.700
&gt;&gt; Okay, is this good?

00:48:24.700 --> 00:48:26.330
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: Why
do we have to stop anyway?

00:48:26.330 --> 00:48:29.270
&gt;&gt; Anyway -- [laughter]

00:48:29.270 --> 00:48:30.860
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: Well,
it's only 20 after seven.

00:48:30.860 --> 00:48:32.160
When is the concert?

00:48:32.160 --> 00:48:33.460
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: Eight,
but we have to open

00:48:33.460 --> 00:48:35.380
up the house at seven thirty.

00:48:35.380 --> 00:48:36.680
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski:
Alright, well -- [laughter]

00:48:36.680 --> 00:48:39.570
&gt;&gt; Okay, so this is a simple one.

00:48:39.570 --> 00:48:44.790 position:56%
You mentioned that if music is
composed for money it won't be good,

00:48:44.790 --> 00:48:48.350
but when I read the writings
of composers of the past,

00:48:48.350 --> 00:48:52.680
like Dvorak comes to mind, he
was very much writing for money.

00:48:52.680 --> 00:48:55.630
He would write about how much he
was going to get for what piece

00:48:55.630 --> 00:49:00.200
and how well he was able to deliver
it on time and it was great music.

00:49:00.200 --> 00:49:03.610
So -- and other people -- I'm
sure you can think of others.

00:49:03.610 --> 00:49:04.910
Has something changed?

00:49:04.910 --> 00:49:07.830
And if so, why?

00:49:07.830 --> 00:49:11.030
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: Well, I
don't know that much about Bartok,

00:49:11.030 --> 00:49:13.340
but some composers aren't --

00:49:13.340 --> 00:49:14.640
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: Dvorak.

00:49:14.640 --> 00:49:15.940
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: Dvorak.

00:49:15.940 --> 00:49:19.310
Oh, Dvorak -- you were
talking -- not Bartok.

00:49:19.310 --> 00:49:22.510
Oh, yeah. Well, I don't know
that much about him either.

00:49:22.510 --> 00:49:27.040
[ Laughter ]

00:49:27.040 --> 00:49:28.980
So, I don't know.

00:49:28.980 --> 00:49:32.550
But some composers
are good businessmen

00:49:32.550 --> 00:49:34.540 position:56%
and there's nothing wrong with that.

00:49:34.540 --> 00:49:40.770
I mean, Philip Glass is both a
good composer, I think, you know --

00:49:40.770 --> 00:49:44.990
although he's certainly not --
everything he wrote is that good,

00:49:44.990 --> 00:49:50.090
but he has done some good stuff and
he's also a very good businessman.

00:49:50.090 --> 00:49:52.960 position:56%
And there's nothing wrong with that.

00:49:52.960 --> 00:49:55.890
In fact I once read an
interview with him --

00:49:55.890 --> 00:50:00.920
or I actually saw it on YouTube
or on the internet or something --

00:50:00.920 --> 00:50:05.000
and somebody asked him something
about like, "Well, you know,

00:50:05.000 --> 00:50:09.350
a lot of your colleagues are
critical of you because you're

00:50:09.350 --> 00:50:13.800
so successful commercially."

00:50:13.800 --> 00:50:18.330
And he said, "Well, actually I
don't see anything wrong with it.

00:50:18.330 --> 00:50:21.930
What's -- [laughs] I'm
not hurting anybody."

00:50:21.930 --> 00:50:23.970
And he went on to explain.

00:50:23.970 --> 00:50:30.290
He said, "You know when I was 15 I
worked in my father's record store

00:50:30.290 --> 00:50:35.860
and what I -- we sold
records to people --

00:50:35.860 --> 00:50:40.970
people would come into the store
wanting music and gave us money

00:50:40.970 --> 00:50:43.590
and I don't see anything
[laughs] wrong with it at all."

00:50:43.590 --> 00:50:46.960
You know he just happened
to, you know,

00:50:46.960 --> 00:50:50.390
learned how to put the
two things together,

00:50:50.390 --> 00:50:54.340
which of course most
composers don't know.

00:50:54.340 --> 00:50:59.210
And he does it well.

00:50:59.210 --> 00:51:01.290
So, it's true.

00:51:01.290 --> 00:51:03.420
I mean there's nothing
wrong with it.

00:51:03.420 --> 00:51:06.360
In fact probably it
would be a good thing

00:51:06.360 --> 00:51:11.330
if people learned how
to sell your music.

00:51:11.330 --> 00:51:14.410
You know, something I've never
really learned, but there --

00:51:14.410 --> 00:51:16.040
I guess you can't really teach it.

00:51:16.040 --> 00:51:19.740
It has to be learned by experience.

00:51:19.740 --> 00:51:21.600
I just know -- all I'm saying is

00:51:21.600 --> 00:51:24.030
that I don't think that
should be the goal.

00:51:24.030 --> 00:51:30.730
I mean you -- it's good if somebody
pays you, of course it's good,

00:51:30.730 --> 00:51:36.410
but if you're doing
something for that purpose --

00:51:39.270 --> 00:51:42.570
[sighs] Well, it's
theoretically possible.

00:51:42.570 --> 00:51:47.350
I mean, Bach wrote his B Minor
Mass certainly for money.

00:51:47.350 --> 00:51:50.050
After all, he was Protestant.

00:51:50.050 --> 00:51:52.980
[laughter] But this was a
-- he wrote a Catholic mass.

00:51:52.980 --> 00:51:58.380
Now the only explanation for that
is that somebody paid him very well

00:51:58.380 --> 00:52:02.980
because he wouldn't normally
do that [laughs] would he?

00:52:02.980 --> 00:52:06.090
[laughter] The fact was
that he was able to do it

00:52:06.090 --> 00:52:08.230
and people were willing
to pay him for it.

00:52:08.230 --> 00:52:10.360
So, I don't know what
the details were,

00:52:10.360 --> 00:52:12.170
but there's nothing wrong with it.

00:52:12.170 --> 00:52:14.640 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: I mean I would
certainly agree that it's a bad idea

00:52:14.640 --> 00:52:16.640
to go into music to make money.

00:52:16.640 --> 00:52:17.940
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: Exactly.

00:52:17.940 --> 00:52:19.240
Precisely.

00:52:19.240 --> 00:52:21.910
&gt;&gt; Charlton Lee: I mean, if you
do wind up making money, great!

00:52:21.910 --> 00:52:25.440
But if you go into
music for the purpose

00:52:25.440 --> 00:52:26.800
of making money that's a dumb idea.

00:52:26.800 --> 00:52:29.170
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: Yes, I think
that's all I was trying to say.

00:52:29.170 --> 00:52:30.590
Yeah, exactly.

00:52:30.590 --> 00:52:34.250
He's got -- he hit
the nail on the head.

00:52:34.250 --> 00:52:35.630
Does that answer the question?

00:52:35.630 --> 00:52:38.330
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: Well,
let's take one more.

00:52:38.330 --> 00:52:40.970
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski:
Yeah, I think you had a --

