And then he was driving
taxis for a while.

00:53:15.580 --> 00:53:20.860
I was living up on Riverside Drive
at a hundred and fifty fifth street

00:53:20.860 --> 00:53:23.510
and when he was in the
neighborhood he would come by

00:53:23.510 --> 00:53:26.260
and we would have a drink together.

00:53:26.260 --> 00:53:27.680
So, I know that.

00:53:27.680 --> 00:53:29.140
I mean I've known him
for a long time.

00:53:29.140 --> 00:53:31.740
&gt;&gt; Well, the story I heard
was somebody was in his taxi

00:53:31.740 --> 00:53:36.510 position:56%
and they said, "You know you have
the same name as a famous composer."

00:53:36.510 --> 00:53:40.050
[ Laughter ]

00:53:40.050 --> 00:53:42.060
But that's not my question.

00:53:42.060 --> 00:53:46.820
My question is that you
have spoken at times

00:53:46.820 --> 00:53:52.720
about a social consciousness or
philosophy that informs your music

00:53:52.720 --> 00:53:55.450
and maybe the 32 variations

00:53:55.450 --> 00:53:59.940
on "The People United Will Never
Be Defeated" is an example of that,

00:53:59.940 --> 00:54:02.800
but I just wondered
where you're at with --

00:54:02.800 --> 00:54:05.670
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: Speaking
too close to the microphone.

00:54:05.670 --> 00:54:08.510
So, you're -- and you're not
speaking loud enough so --

00:54:08.510 --> 00:54:12.280
[ Inaudible Answer ]

00:54:12.280 --> 00:54:13.580
What? [inaudible answer]

00:54:13.580 --> 00:54:22.120
&gt;&gt; My question was about having
a social message in your music.

00:54:22.120 --> 00:54:24.600
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski:
What is the question?

00:54:24.600 --> 00:54:25.900
[laughter]

00:54:25.900 --> 00:54:29.180
&gt;&gt; Whether that's an
important thing to you now.

00:54:29.180 --> 00:54:30.480
I mean I think that --

00:54:30.480 --> 00:54:31.790
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: To
have a social message?

00:54:31.790 --> 00:54:33.090
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:54:33.090 --> 00:54:35.260
&gt;&gt; Frederic Rzewski: Well, if
you have one it's important

00:54:35.260 --> 00:54:40.030
to speak it out, but you
don't have to have one.

00:54:41.100 --> 00:54:46.370
It's not necessary to make music
-- to have a social message.

00:54:46.370 --> 00:54:51.740
You can write music about
love, death, a lot of things,

00:54:51.740 --> 00:54:57.390
but if you have a social message
and you can use music as a way

00:54:57.390 --> 00:55:03.760
of expressing it, it's -- well
it's like what Jesus Christ says,

00:55:03.760 --> 00:55:07.060
you know; if you have the
light you should not hide it

00:55:07.060 --> 00:55:09.530
under a bushel, whatever
a bushel is.

00:55:09.530 --> 00:55:15.040
[laughter] It's the same
thing in art or music.

00:55:15.040 --> 00:55:21.410
I mean you -- Oscar Wilde
says, "Expression is all."

00:55:21.410 --> 00:55:28.560
So, many people have -- and Pablo
Neruda in his autobiography talks

00:55:28.560 --> 00:55:32.070
about how he meets a worker
who recognizes him and says

00:55:32.070 --> 00:55:37.470
that he too would like to be a
poet and Neruda tells him, "Well,

00:55:37.470 --> 00:55:42.250
you are a poet, everybody is a
poet because everybody dreams.

00:55:42.250 --> 00:55:45.890
The only difference between
a poet and other people is

00:55:45.890 --> 00:55:48.490 position:56%
that poets write their dreams down."

00:55:48.490 --> 00:55:51.770
So, that's all it is really.

00:55:51.770 --> 00:55:56.140
So, yeah if you have
something to say about society

00:55:56.140 --> 00:56:03.830
and you can use music to say
it, why this is a good thing,

00:56:03.830 --> 00:56:09.810
but of course not everybody
does that

00:56:09.810 --> 00:56:13.800
and there's no reason
why they should.

00:56:13.800 --> 00:56:16.000
Some people do.

00:56:16.000 --> 00:56:21.670
Verdi wrote Nabucco, one of his
early operas and there's a chorus

00:56:21.670 --> 00:56:26.570
in it of the Jews who are
lamenting, who are crying about how

00:56:26.570 --> 00:56:31.780
on the shores of Babylon --
they're on the shores of Babylon

00:56:31.780 --> 00:56:35.390
and so forth, and thinking
about their homeland

00:56:35.390 --> 00:56:40.750
and that became the Risorgimento.

00:56:40.750 --> 00:56:44.710
It's -- began the Italian
Revolutionary Movement.

00:56:44.710 --> 00:56:50.590
And so you know it happens.

00:56:50.590 --> 00:56:55.650
Pierre De Geyter was asked
by the International --

00:56:55.650 --> 00:57:00.290
Socialist International to write a
worker's hymn for the International

00:57:00.290 --> 00:57:06.170
and he brought in a kind of folk
song like melody and they said,

00:57:06.170 --> 00:57:09.340
[derisive noise] "This
is too low class.

00:57:09.340 --> 00:57:15.250
You should write something that's
similar to La Marseillaise."

00:57:15.250 --> 00:57:17.200
[laughter] So, he went
back to the drawing board

00:57:17.200 --> 00:57:25.820
and he wrote the International,
which had a notable career.

00:57:25.820 --> 00:57:28.790
It's now sort of forgotten, but --

00:57:28.790 --> 00:57:32.420
and he never received
a penny from it.

00:57:32.420 --> 00:57:38.110
A German businessman realized
that sometime in the 60s,

00:57:38.110 --> 00:57:42.640
realized that this song had
never been copywrited [laughter]

00:57:42.640 --> 00:57:48.330
and there was still a feel
years left in international law.

00:57:48.330 --> 00:57:53.260
So, he went and copywrited it
and for the next few years he,

00:57:53.260 --> 00:57:55.220
every time the song was played

00:57:55.220 --> 00:58:01.120
in a Romanian movie
theater, he got money.

00:58:04.480 --> 00:58:05.890
[laughter] Why not?

00:58:05.890 --> 00:58:11.600
Well, look I mean Warner
Communications has just recently --

00:58:11.600 --> 00:58:16.950
a federal judge just a
month ago or so decided

00:58:16.950 --> 00:58:20.650
that Warner Communications had
no right to collect royalties

00:58:20.650 --> 00:58:25.990
on Happy Birthday, which
was written by a housewife

00:58:25.990 --> 00:58:30.160
in Illinois around 1880 something.

00:58:30.160 --> 00:58:35.200
There's absolutely [laughs] no
reason why [laughs] anybody should

00:58:35.200 --> 00:58:39.000
get any money for it,
but they were doing it.

00:58:39.000 --> 00:58:42.240
Anyway we'll -- [laughter]

00:58:42.240 --> 00:58:43.540
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: Well,
just because of the time --

00:58:43.540 --> 00:58:47.940
we do have a concert that shortly
and we have to change over the room

00:58:47.940 --> 00:58:49.240
as well, but please join me

00:58:49.240 --> 00:58:51.510
in thanking Frederic
Rzewski and Charlton Lee.

